# Writing Tests in Playwright
1️⃣ Introduction
Writing tests in Playwright is simple and follows pytest conventions.
A Playwright test mainly contains
---------------------------------
    1. Navigation -> Opens a webpage
    2. Actions -> Interact with element
    3. Assertions -> Verify expected results
Playwright automatically waits for elements before performing actions , so manual waits are usually not required.

2️⃣ Basic Test Example
Example Playwright test
-----------------------
import re
from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright , Page , expect
def test_has_title(page : Page):
    page.goto("https://example.com")
    expect(page).to_have_title(re.compile("Playwright"))

Explanation
-----------
    Page
        -> Represents the browser page

    page.goto()
        -> Opens the given URL
    
    expect()
        -> Used to verify expected results
    
3️⃣ Writing Multiple Tests
A single file can contain multiple test functions.
Example
-------
    import re
    from playwright.sync_api import Page , expect , sync_playwright
    def test_has_title(page : Page):
        page.goto("https://playwright.dev/")
        expect(page).to_have_title(re.compile("Playwright"))
    
    def test_get_started(page : Page):
        page.goto("https://playwright.dev/")
        page.get_by_role("link", name = "Get Started").click()
        expect(page.get_by_role("heading" , name = "Installation")).to_be_visible()
Each function represents one test case.

4️⃣ Test File Naming Rules
Playwright follows pytest naming conventions
File name must starts with
--------------------------
    test_
    Example:
        test_login.py
        test_homepage.py
        test_search.py

Function name must also starts with
-----------------------------------
    test_
    Example:
        def test_login(page : Page):
    
5️⃣ Test Structure in Real Projects
In real playwright Projects , tests are usually organized like this.
Project Structure
-----------------
project/
│
├── tests/
│   ├── test_login.py
│   ├── test_homepage.py
│   └── test_checkout.py
│
├── pages/
│   └── login_page.py
│
├── conftest.py
└── pytest.ini

Explanation
-----------
tests/
    Contains test scripts

pages/
    Page Object Model files

conftest.py
    Shared fixtures for tests

6️⃣ Navigation in Tests
Most tests begin by opening a website.
Example
-------
    page.goto("https://example.com")
Playwright automatically waits for the page to load before performing any actions.

7️⃣ Performing Actions
Actions are performed using locators.
Example
-------
    page.get_by_role("link" , name = "Get Started").click()

Steps:
------
    1. Locate the element
    2. Perform action on the element

Commom actions
--------------
    Action & Description
    --------------------
    1. locator.click() -> Click element
    2. locator.fill() -> Enter text
    3. locator.hover() -> hover mouse
    4. locator.press() -> Press keyboard key
    5. locator.check() -> Check checkbox
    6. locator.select_option() -> Select dropdown option

8️⃣ Assertions
Assertions verify the expected results.
Example
-------
    expect(page).to_have_title("Playwright")

Example locator assertion
    expect(locator).to_be_visible()

Common Assertions
-----------------
    Assertion & Description
    -----------------------
    1. expect(locator).to_be_visible() -> element is visible
    2. expect(locator).to_have_text() -> Check text
    3. expect(locator).to_be_enabled() -> Element enabled
    4. expect(locator).to_have_title() -> Verify title
    5. expect(locator).to_have_url() -> Verify page URL
Playwright assertions automatically retry until the condition is satisfied.

9️⃣ Test Isolation
Each playwright test runs in separate browser context
Meaning
-------
    -> Every test starts with a fresh browser environment

Benefits
--------
    1. Tests do not affect each other
    2. Data is not shared between tests
    3. Reduces flaky tests

🔟 Using Fixtures
Playwright integrates with pytest fixtures.
Example
-------
    import re
    from playwright.sync_api import Page
    @pytest.fixture
    def open_home(page : Page):
        page.goto("https://playwright.dev")
        yield
    
Fixtures are used for
    1. Setup before tests
    2. Clean after tests
    3. Reusing test code

1️⃣1️⃣ Key Points
Important things to remember
    1. Test files must start with "test_"
    2. Test functions must start with "test_"
    3. Use page fixtures for browser interaction
    4. Use locator to find elements
    5. Use expect() for assertion
    6. Each test runs in isolated browser context
    
